<h2>The block-page rhythm</h2>

<p>Every block page (one per day of class, ~80 minutes each) follows the same five-section template:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Story.</strong> Why this block matters. The connection back to the unit's anchor question.</li>
  <li><strong>Concepts.</strong> Three ways in — watch, read, interact. Pick one or mix and match.</li>
  <li><strong>Do.</strong> Today's work. A choice board, usually 4 options that all build toward the same Learning Intention.</li>
  <li><strong>Show.</strong> What you're submitting today and how it's scored.</li>
  <li><strong>Reflect.</strong> One question before you leave. No grade. Builds the metacognitive close that makes tomorrow easier.</li>
</ul>

<p>Every block page also has an <strong>AI Partners callout</strong> at the top — the partners relevant for that day's work — and a <strong>bottom navigation</strong> with the previous block, the unit map, and the next block.</p>

<h2>Finding things quickly</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Looking for today's work?</strong> Top nav → Course Units → your unit → today's block page.</li>
  <li><strong>Looking up a term?</strong> Top nav → Reference → Glossary.</li>
  <li><strong>Need the rubric while writing?</strong> Top nav → Student Hub → Rubric Quick Reference.</li>
  <li><strong>Need to fill out AI Documentation?</strong> Top nav → Student Hub → AI Documentation Template.</li>
  <li><strong>Forgotten how OPVL works?</strong> Top nav → Foundations → OPVL Framework.</li>
</ul>

